            "image": "assets/pages/fce-051.jpg",
            "transcript": "A light breeze ruffled the steel-blue ocean. Roy Mason looked out over the beach, hands curled round his second mug of tea of the day. The first had been just before he left his tiny stone cottage high up in one of the winding streets that made up the village of Everdene. If he could have had a pound for every time someone stuck a note through his door asking if he wanted to sell, he would have been able to afford one of the posh new homes that were being built on the top road, had he wanted one. The developer's sign proudly boasted that nearly all of them had been sold.\n\nThere might be a problem selling houses in the rest of the country, but not here. Not when the air smelled sweet, the surrounding hills were soft and rolling and the view took your breath away. Roy wouldn't tire of it, Not that he’d ever seen much else. The writing on his mug might say that he loved New York, but he’d never been. His sister had brought it back when she'd been on a shopping trip there. Roy was happy that she’d enjoyed the experience but he failed to see what all the fuss was about.\n\nHe drained the last of the sugary tea, put down the mug and collected up his tools — proper tools, with wooden handles that had moulded themselves to fit his hands over time, smooth and solid beneath his fingers, not like the lightweight plastic ones they sold that snapped and bent as soon as you put them to use.\n\nTo Roy’s mind, there was no point in doing something unless you gave it your best. He never cut corners.\n\nHe did things properly. The same couldn't be said of everyone. For instance, someone last year put an advertisement in the local village shop undercutting his prices, and a few of the chalet owners had been tempted. The guy might have been cheap but he was clumsy and inexperienced. Roy had watched him attempting to hang a new door. It was comical. He felt sorry for him. He was only trying to make living, but he hadn't a clue. In the end, he'd given up, gone off and Roy had picked up with the old customers where he’d left off, no hard feelings, nothing said. He wasn’t one to bear a grudge.\n\nRoy's father had built the wooden beach chalets and Roy was the unofficial c: ker, doing e and repairs. Some owners were mean and only paid for their chalet to be repaired once every three or four years. A false economy. The wind and rain that swept through over the winter was unforgiving; the wood needed protection. Some owners kept their chalets plain; others saw it as an excuse to express their personality and chose garish colours that somehow worked in the seaside setting, a fairground riot of reds and greens and pinks and oranges. Some of them had their own names. Nothing sparklingly original, but it added to the sense that this was a community, that each chalet was a home from home.\n\nHe usually spent the morning working on the chalets. At night he took people fishing for sea bass. It satisfied an inner longing in them, particularly younger men looking for new experiences. There was something about fishing that appealed to them and Roy found their enthusiasm infectious. Older people rarely took to it in the same way — they were always slightly mystified by the attraction, if they ever ventured out. He could see they were cold and bored. They would much rather buy their sea bass from an old van that drove along the coast road every evening.\n\nHis mobile rang in the pocket of his shorts; another reason for the popularity of this beach -a good phone signal for all those career people who needed to keep in touch with the office. Roy didn’t see the point. It wasn't a holiday if your employers could check up on you or if you could check up on them. But that seemed to be the way of the world.\n\na"
